Here’s a step-by-step way to set up an Auto Scaling Group (ASG) in AWS, in a simple, interview-friendly way?

1. Create a Launch Template or Launch Configuration
A Launch Template defines how your EC2 instances should launch:
AMI (Amazon Machine Image)
Instance type (t2.micro, t3.large, etc.)
Key pair for SSH
Security group
User data (optional startup scripts)
EBS volume
Packages

Tip: Launch Templates are preferred over Launch Configurations—they’re more flexible.

2. Create the Auto Scaling Group
Go to EC2 → Auto Scaling → Auto Scaling Groups → Create ASG
Choose the Launch Template
Set minimum, maximum, and desired capacity:
Min → minimum instances to always run
Max → maximum allowed
Desired → initially running instances
Select VPC and Subnets
Choose multiple Availability Zones for high availability

3. Attach Load Balancer (Optional but Recommended)
Integrate with Elastic Load Balancer (ELB) so traffic distributes evenly across instances
Health checks:
EC2 health check
ELB health check

ASG automatically replaces unhealthy instances.

4. Set Scaling Policies in ASG
Dynamic scaling: add/remove instances based on CloudWatch metrics
Example: CPU > 70% → add 2 instances
CPU < 30% → remove 1 instance
Scheduled scaling: scale at fixed times
Example: Black Friday traffic spike
Target tracking scaling: maintain a target metric (like CPU 50%)

During creation:
  ✅ Target Tracking → available
  ❌ Step Scaling    → not available
  ❌ Scheduled       → not available

After creation:
  ✅ Target Tracking → available
  ✅ Step Scaling    → available
  ✅ Scheduled       → available
-------------------------------------
Types of scaling policy
------------------------------------
Target Tracking Scaling
→ automatically scales to maintain a target metric value
  example: keep CPU at 70% always ✅

Step Scaling
→ scales by different amounts based on how high the metric goes
  example: CPU 70% add 1, CPU 90% add 5 ✅

Scheduled Scaling
→ scales at a specific time you define
  example: every Monday 9am add 10 instances ✅

Simple Scaling
→ old way — waits for cooldown period before scaling again
  example: CPU high → add 1 → wait 300 seconds → check again ❌ not recommended
-------------------------------------------------
Enable Notifications (Optional)
Use SNS to get notifications when scaling happens
Helps monitor and audit scaling events
